Blueprints use web items to appear inside the Create dialog. You can use a condition in this web item to control the visibility of the blueprint. Currently there is only the space (as selected in the Create dialog) and the curent user available in the condition's context.

Since the Create dialog is called in the context of a specific page it would be great to have the current page available in this context.

In my specific case, I wrote a condition that renders true when a specific macro is being used on the current page.


*Workaround*
My little hacky workaround is as follows. 

First of all, the current page's id must be transmitted via the REST request for the web-items. I used this code to override the default request code:

{code:javascript}
AJS.toInit(function ($) {

    Confluence.Blueprint.Dialog.requestWebItems = function requestWebItems(spaceKey) {
        Confluence.Blueprint.Dialog.loadedWebitems = Confluence.Blueprint.Dialog.loadedWebitems || {};
        var data = Confluence.Blueprint.Dialog.loadedWebitems[spaceKey];
        if (data) {
            return AJS.$.Deferred().resolveWith(data);
        }
        return $.ajax({
            url: Confluence.getContextPath() + "/rest/create-dialog/1.0/blueprints/web-items",
            dataType: "json",
            data: {
                spaceKey: spaceKey,

                //////////////////////////////////////
                //////////////////////////////////////
                // THIS IS THE NEW PARAMETER /////////
                currentPageId: AJS.Meta.get('page-id')
                //////////////////////////////////////
                //////////////////////////////////////
            }
        }).done(function(data) {
            Confluence.Blueprint.Dialog.loadedWebitems[spaceKey] = data;
        });
    };
});
{code}

Inside my condition I have the following method to get the associated Page object:

{code:java}
    private Page getCurrentPage() {

        HttpServletRequest request = ServletContextThreadLocal.getRequest();

        long currentPageId = 0L;
        try {
            // note: this parameter is only there because of the overridden JavaScript functionality (see blueprint-wizard.js)
            currentPageId = Integer.parseInt(request.getParameter(PARAM_PAGEID));
        }
        catch (Exception e) {

            // page id could not be parsed --> no current page available
            LOG.warn("Error while parsing the current page id", e);
            return null;
        }

        return pageManager.getPage(currentPageId);
    }
{code}

